<TEXT>
heavy fog that halted air traffic at 
seattletacoma international airport and disrupted travel plans for 
thousands of passengers lifted saturday night allowing some flights 
to resume 
a slight change in upper atmosphere winds helped clear the fog 
about 12 hours earlier than expected national weather service 
forecaster hank treick said 
visibility at the airport improved from near zero to five miles 
and some planes landed beginning about 8 pm treick said fog could 
create more delays overnight but the worst of it had passed 
abner thomas airport supervisor at seatac said late saturday 
afternoon that there were few planes on the ground because there was 
no traffic getting in minimum restrictions are not as severe for 
aircraft taking off as for planes that are landing so the airlines 
got their planes out of seattle when they could 
by midafternoon only two flights had been able to land because 
the fog restricted visibility below the minimum of 700 feet 
some incoming flights were diverted to moses lake portland 
ore and vancouver british columbia where the passengers were 
given the option of either getting to seattle by bus or waiting to 
see if the fog cleared at seatac 
</TEXT>
