gunmen stormed the home of a prominent 
opposition politician who once belonged to the ruling party and 
killed five people sunday and 19 other people were slain in 
preelection violence police said 
seven people were critically wounded in the attack on a campaign 
meeting at the home of neville fernando in panadura nine miles 
south of colombo said police who spoke on condition of anonymity 
fernando was hospitalized for shock 
panadura police blamed the attack on the peoples liberation 
front a group of sinhalese extremists that has vowed to stop 
mondays presidential election fernando a sinhalese formerly 
belonged to president junius r jayewardenes united national party 
but left it to work for the freedom party headed by presidential 
candidate and former prime minister sirimavo bandaranaike 
nineteen other people were killed in a series of attacks in the 
sinhalese heartland of central and southern sri lanka according to 
officials who spoke on condition of anonymity 
the victims included two sri lankan soldiers killed sunday in an 
attack on a polling center in kamburapitiya 75 miles southeast of 
colombo and two soldiers killed sunday near epawellia about 90 
miles northeast of colombo the officials blamed both attacks on the 
peoples liberation front 
six people including two united national party workers were 
killed saturday near monaragala about 100 miles east of colombo 
the bodies of nine suspected sinhalese extremists were found in 
several locations in southern sri lanka on sunday according to the 
officials who gave no indication who was behind the killings 
the peoples liberation front opposes jayewardene for signing an 
accord last year that granted some autonomy to the minority tamils 
and has vowed to kill anyone supporting the pact 
it also opposes mondays election saying it wont be conducted 
fairly under jayewardene 
sinhalese make up 75 percent of the islands population and 
dominate the government and military tamils comprise 18 percent 
