a group of doctors 
firefighters rescue workers and specially trained dogs returned 
sunday from soviet armenia where they spent a week assisting with 
efforts to rescue victims of a devastating earthquake 
ten firefighters from fairfax va eight firefighters from 
miami fla eight dogs and their 12 handlers were aboard a 
chartered 727 that arrived at andrews air force base outside 
washington at 831 am several doctors also were aboard but 
officials could not immediately say how many 
its hard to put into words the absolute total devastation of 
the area said michael tamillow a member of the group who said he 
led a rescue team a private car going down the street with a 
coffin on top it was those kind of things that brought things 
together 
tamillow said he was amazed at the resilience of the armenian 
people and credited soviet troops with helping rescue workers from 
the united states and other countries 
the team was assembled dec 9 two days after the earthquake at 
the request of the office of foreign assistance an arm of the 
agency for international development 
a military transport team took the team to leninakan a soviet 
city virtually destroyed by the earthquake which may have killed up 
to 55000 people and left an estimated 500000 homeless 
the group began preparing for the trip home on friday after 
soviet officials determined there was little chance of finding 
additional survivors the dogs are trained to find survivors in the 
rubble 
at the base to greet the team were members of their families and 
coworkers many waited several hours because of delays in the 
flight also on hand were members of the armenian relief society a 
group based in watertown mass society representatives presented 
the rescue workers with christmas baskets containing fruit cheese 
and candies 
in a related development the armenian group said 20 kidney 
dialysis machines and other medical supplies were flown to the 
soviet union sunday on an aeroflot flight that left from andrews a 
team of medical experts left separately from newark nj the 
organization said food and clothing donated by private industry 
were aboard that flight 
