<TEXT>
seventeenyearold arnel galang still 
wakes up screaming haunted by the faces of the 23 relatives he lost 
a year ago when the ferry dona paz sank with more than 3000 people 
aboard 
arnel then a high school senior was one of only 26 passengers 
and crew who survived after the 2215ton dona paz collided with the 
629ton oil tanker vector and exploded off mindoro island the night 
of dec 20 1987 
a presidential commission said at least 3563 people were aboard 
the two ships but the precise figure may never be known only 108 
bodies were recovered after the disaster which the coast guard 
blamed on the vector 
for arnel the year has been one of bitterness and pain he feels 
abandoned by a government that he says has done little to help him 
family members blame arnel for not saving his relatives 
including cousins aunts and an infant niece who perished on the 
dona paz 
everything that happened is still clear to me he said his 
hands trembling sometimes i cant sleep sometimes i get 
nightmares i shout and cry then i stay awake all night in my 
dreams they tell me they have not died only wandered off to an 
unknown place but i have to face reality i just pray for them 
arnel and his relatives boarded the dona paz to go to manila to 
visit his sister rose whom he hadnt seen since childhood it was 
his first time on a ship 
suddenly about 10 pm he felt a strong thud 
he ran for a wall and squeezed himself through a porthole 
i struggled free and fell into the water he recalled i 
couldnt hear anything anymore there was just silence the sea was 
on fire my face was scalded the water was very hot as if it were 
boiling water i swam so fast i dont know how i did it 
arnel and the other survivors were rescued by a passing ship and 
brought to manila there he saw rose burned and bandaged he raced 
to embrace her 
but the joy of reunion soon gave way to resentment relatives 
blamed him for not saving other family members 
they ask me arnel why did you not save your cousins he 
said fighting back tears i tell themthere was nothing i could 
do it was difficult enough saving myself maybe if i tried to save 
them we would all have died 
since the disaster arnel said he has shunned other relatives 
including his parents who live in manila 
arnel is also bitter at the government which he says abandoned 
him he received 5000 pesos or 250 which president corazon 
aquino allocated for each survivor but he said there has been no 
psychological counseling or rehabilitation for the survivors 
mrs aquino recommended arnel for a job in a pharmacy but the 
company refused to hire him his family is too poor to afford fees 
to complete his final year of high school he works as an unpaid 
volunteer for an association of relatives of dona paz victims and 
survives on charity 
arnel said he and some relatives of victims have refused to 
accept a 1500 lump sum payment from the shipowners sulpicio 
shipping lines because the company insists they sign a waiver 
promising no further claims 
in april a group of survivors and relatives filed a class action 
suit seeking more compensation the case was dismissed and an appeal 
is pending before the supreme court 
in the meantime arnel is considering becoming a priest 
when i think about the things ive gone through and am going 
through i think that maybe god wants me to be a priest and serve 
him he said at this point i have nothing else to lose and i 
am ready to offer my life 
the sense of loneliness and abandonment is all the more painful 
at christmas 
last christmas five days after the tragedy arnel spent the day 
crying in a corner of his parents home gazing out the window this 
year he plans to spend the holiday alone 
i cant bear to face them again he said 
