<TEXT>
the quebec government said sunday it 
will keep a partial prohibition on nonfrench store signs even 
though the nations highest court struck down the ban 
the issue has threatened to deepen divisions once again between 
the englishspeaking minority and the frenchspeaking majority of 
this eastern canadian province 
quebecs government decided sunday to override provincial and 
federal charters of rights to keep the ban on outdoor signs 
however the compromise proposal would allow merchants to post 
bilingual signs indoors 
to govern is to choose quebec premier robert bourassa told a 
sunday afternoon news conference broadcast live on quebec television 
and radio we are not happy to impose that solution 
the provincial government was reacting to a ruling thursday by 
the supreme court of canada which struck down quebecs frenchonly 
sign law 
the issue has posed the most difficult political test for 
bourassa since the election of his liberal party three years ago 
the courts decision was followed by a hectic weekend of meetings 
of political leaders and provincial cabinet members bourassa fought 
to block a damaging split in the party and a walkout by 
englishspeaking members 
the provincial government is asking an enormous concession 
from the provinces english speakers bourassa said sunday but he 
said frenchspeaking quebecers are still too insecure about the 
future of their language for the provincial government to allow 
bilingual signs outside stores 
opposition parti quebecois house leader guy chevrette denounced 
the new plan saying the provincial government has taken the most 
pernicious and hypocritical route to the anglicization of 
quebec the party once championed a movement for quebec 
independence from canada but it has moderated those views in recent 
years 
royal orr president of the englishrights lobby alliance 
quebec also condemned the decision which overrides linguistic 
freedoms established in quebecs own charter of rights 
you and your government are without principle without the 
courage to do what is right and without the quality and integrity 
of leadership which command respect he said 
orr said the quebec governments moral convictions should have 
outweighed its legal right to use the notwithstanding clauses in 
the two rights charters 
those clauses in the federal and quebec charters allow the 
province to override freedomofexpression sections in both 
documents 
bourassa wanted to work out a compromise that would please 
hardline elements in his caucus who wanted no changes in the sign 
law as well as englishspeakers who urged the provincial government 
to live up to a 1985 electoral pledge to allow bilingual signs both 
inside and outside stores 
bourassa whose liberals lost power to the parti quebecois in 
1976 partly because of language issue held out hope that one day 
there might be no ban on languages other than french on outside 
commercial signs but he added i cannot commit myself to a 
calendar 
he also delivered an emotional appeal to englishspeaking members 
of his caucus to remain in his government saying we need you 
provincial government leaders say they will quickly put forward 
new legislation to turn the proposed partial ban into law 
