<TEXT>
the nations major airlines are ready to end their 
triple mileage programs but only if all the carriers do so 
according to some airline officials 
the programs in which airlines give frequent fliers three miles 
of credit for each mile they fly have been popular with the flying 
public and costly for the major carriers 
delta air lines introduced triple mileage about a year ago and 
the others quickly followed suit 
triple miles truly sent a shock through the airline industry 
and through american airlines michael gunn americans senior 
vice president of marketing told the dallas morning news it was 
fundamentally unsound from an economic standpoint 
deltas frequent flier membership increased by 25 million during 
1988 and americans jumped by 15 million the morning news 
reported in sundays editions 
last april several carriers announced changes that effectively 
pulled in the reins on free flying and airlines could be ready now 
to eliminate the triple mileage programs entirely some experts say 
triple miles will pass into legend on dec 31st matt 
guilfoyle deltas director of consumer marketing said last week 
as delta proved a year ago only one airline has to break away 
from the herd to start a stampede 
there will be a move to slowly and i mean slowly tighten 
the use of frequent flier mileage said paul karos an airline 
analyst with first boston corp but the airlines arent going to 
be able to get rid of the programs totally nor would they want to 
theyre a good marketing tool 
analysts estimate that the potential cost of all frequent flier 
miles when translated into free tickets and service upgrades 
could approach 1 billion as much as half of that total is 
attributable to triple mileage bonuses 
at the same time it appears increasingly likely that the 
organization that sets accounting standards for us businesses the 
american institute of certified public accountants will soon 
require airlines to list their potential frequent flier liabilities 
on their balance sheets 
in response airlines are likely to find ways to remove the 
mileage awards from their books by putting an expiration date on 
miles already earned or by putting a time limit on the use of future 
mileage awards 
airlines also are increasing the use of blackout dates 
popular travel periods when tickets obtained as frequent flier 
awards cannot be used and capacity control with capacity control 
airlines limit the number of seats on each flight to be given away 
to frequent fliers 
